docs/community/faq.rst-73-
docs/community/faq.rst:74:These errors occur when :ref:`SSL certificate verification <verification>`
docs/community/faq.rst:75:fails to match the certificate the server responds with to the hostname
docs/community/faq.rst:76:Requests thinks it's contacting. If you're certain the server's SSL setup is
docs/community/faq.rst-77-correct (for example, because you can visit the site with your browser) and
docs/community/faq.rst-78-you're using Python 2.7, a possible explanation is that you need
docs/community/faq.rst-79-Server-Name-Indication.
docs/community/faq.rst-80-
docs/community/faq.rst:81:`Server-Name-Indication`_, or SNI, is an official extension to SSL where the
docs/community/faq.rst-82-client tells the server what hostname it is contacting. This is important
docs/community/faq.rst-83-when servers are using `Virtual Hosting`_. When such servers are hosting
docs/community/faq.rst:84:more than one SSL site they need to be able to return the appropriate
docs/community/faq.rst:85:certificate based on the hostname the client is connecting to.
docs/community/faq.rst-86-
docs/community/faq.rst:87:Python 3 already includes native support for SNI in their SSL modules.
docs/community/faq.rst-88-
docs/community/faq.rst-89-.. _`Server-Name-Indication`: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Server_Name_Indication
