docs/user/advanced.rst-189-
docs/user/advanced.rst-190-When you are using the prepared request flow, keep in mind that it does not take into account the environment.
docs/user/advanced.rst-191-This can cause problems if you are using environment variables to change the behaviour of requests.
docs/user/advanced.rst:192:For example: Self-signed SSL certificates specified in ``REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE`` will not be taken into account.
docs/user/advanced.rst:193:As a result an ``SSL: CERTIFICATE_VERIFY_FAILED`` is thrown.
docs/user/advanced.rst-194-You can get around this behaviour by explicitly merging the environment settings into your session::
docs/user/advanced.rst-195-
docs/user/advanced.rst-196-    from requests import Request, Session
--
docs/user/advanced.rst-208-
docs/user/advanced.rst-209-.. _verification:
docs/user/advanced.rst-210-
docs/user/advanced.rst:211:SSL Cert Verification
docs/user/advanced.rst-212----------------------
docs/user/advanced.rst-213-
docs/user/advanced.rst:214:Requests verifies SSL certificates for HTTPS requests, just like a web browser.
docs/user/advanced.rst:215:By default, SSL verification is enabled, and Requests will throw a SSLError if
docs/user/advanced.rst:216:it's unable to verify the certificate::
docs/user/advanced.rst-217-
docs/user/advanced.rst-218-    >>> requests.get('https://requestb.in')
docs/user/advanced.rst:219:    requests.exceptions.SSLError: hostname 'requestb.in' doesn't match either of '*.herokuapp.com', 'herokuapp.com'
docs/user/advanced.rst-220-
docs/user/advanced.rst:221:I don't have SSL setup on this domain, so it throws an exception. Excellent. GitHub does though::
docs/user/advanced.rst-222-
docs/user/advanced.rst-223-    >>> requests.get('https://github.com')
docs/user/advanced.rst-224-    <Response [200]>
docs/user/advanced.rst-225-
docs/user/advanced.rst:226:You can pass ``verify`` the path to a CA_BUNDLE file or directory with certificates of trusted CAs::
docs/user/advanced.rst-227-
docs/user/advanced.rst-228-    >>> requests.get('https://github.com', verify='/path/to/certfile')
docs/user/advanced.rst-229-
--
docs/user/advanced.rst-233-    s.verify = '/path/to/certfile'
docs/user/advanced.rst-234-
docs/user/advanced.rst-235-.. note:: If ``verify`` is set to a path to a directory, the directory must have been processed using
docs/user/advanced.rst:236:  the ``c_rehash`` utility supplied with OpenSSL.
docs/user/advanced.rst-237-
docs/user/advanced.rst-238-This list of trusted CAs can also be specified through the ``REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE`` environment variable.
docs/user/advanced.rst-239-If ``REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE`` is not set, ``CURL_CA_BUNDLE`` will be used as fallback.
docs/user/advanced.rst-240-
docs/user/advanced.rst:241:Requests can also ignore verifying the SSL certificate if you set ``verify`` to False::
docs/user/advanced.rst-242-
docs/user/advanced.rst:243:    >>> requests.get('https://kennethreitz.org', verify=False)
docs/user/advanced.rst-244-    <Response [200]>
docs/user/advanced.rst-245-
docs/user/advanced.rst-246-Note that when ``verify`` is set to ``False``, requests will accept any TLS
docs/user/advanced.rst:247:certificate presented by the server, and will ignore hostname mismatches
docs/user/advanced.rst:248:and/or expired certificates, which will make your application vulnerable to
docs/user/advanced.rst-249-man-in-the-middle (MitM) attacks. Setting verify to ``False`` may be useful
docs/user/advanced.rst-250-during local development or testing.
docs/user/advanced.rst-251-
docs/user/advanced.rst-252-By default, ``verify`` is set to True. Option ``verify`` only applies to host certs.
docs/user/advanced.rst-253-
docs/user/advanced.rst:254:Client Side Certificates
docs/user/advanced.rst-255-------------------------
docs/user/advanced.rst-256-
docs/user/advanced.rst:257:You can also specify a local cert to use as client side certificate, as a single
docs/user/advanced.rst:258:file (containing the private key and the certificate) or as a tuple of both
docs/user/advanced.rst-259-files' paths::
docs/user/advanced.rst-260-
docs/user/advanced.rst-261-    >>> requests.get('https://kennethreitz.org', cert=('/path/client.cert', '/path/client.key'))
--
docs/user/advanced.rst-266-    s = requests.Session()
docs/user/advanced.rst-267-    s.cert = '/path/client.cert'
docs/user/advanced.rst-268-
docs/user/advanced.rst:269:If you specify a wrong path or an invalid cert, you'll get a SSLError::
docs/user/advanced.rst-270-
docs/user/advanced.rst-271-    >>> requests.get('https://kennethreitz.org', cert='/wrong_path/client.pem')
docs/user/advanced.rst:272:    SSLError: [Errno 336265225] _ssl.c:347: error:140B0009:SSL routines:SSL_CTX_use_PrivateKey_file:PEM lib
docs/user/advanced.rst-273-
docs/user/advanced.rst:274:.. warning:: The private key to your local certificate *must* be unencrypted.
docs/user/advanced.rst-275-   Currently, Requests does not support using encrypted keys.
docs/user/advanced.rst-276-
docs/user/advanced.rst:277:.. _ca-certificates:
docs/user/advanced.rst-278-
docs/user/advanced.rst:279:CA Certificates
docs/user/advanced.rst-280----------------
docs/user/advanced.rst-281-
docs/user/advanced.rst:282:Requests uses certificates from the package `certifi`_. This allows for users
docs/user/advanced.rst:283:to update their trusted certificates without changing the version of Requests.
docs/user/advanced.rst-284-
docs/user/advanced.rst-285-Before version 2.16, Requests bundled a set of root CAs that it trusted,
docs/user/advanced.rst:286:sourced from the `Mozilla trust store`_. The certificates were only updated
docs/user/advanced.rst:287:once for each Requests version. When ``certifi`` was not installed, this led to
docs/user/advanced.rst:288:extremely out-of-date certificate bundles when using significantly older
docs/user/advanced.rst-289-versions of Requests.
docs/user/advanced.rst-290-
docs/user/advanced.rst:291:For the sake of security we recommend upgrading certifi frequently!
docs/user/advanced.rst-292-
docs/user/advanced.rst-293-.. _HTTP persistent connection: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_persistent_connection
