docs/user/advanced.rst-651-Note that proxy URLs must include the scheme.
docs/user/advanced.rst-652-
docs/user/advanced.rst-653-Finally, note that using a proxy for https connections typically requires your
docs/user/advanced.rst:654:local machine to trust the proxy's root certificate. By default the list of
docs/user/advanced.rst:655:certificates trusted by Requests can be found with::
docs/user/advanced.rst-656-
docs/user/advanced.rst-657-    from requests.utils import DEFAULT_CA_BUNDLE_PATH
docs/user/advanced.rst-658-    print(DEFAULT_CA_BUNDLE_PATH)
docs/user/advanced.rst-659-
docs/user/advanced.rst:660:You override this default certificate bundle by setting the ``REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE``
docs/user/advanced.rst-661-(or ``CURL_CA_BUNDLE``) environment variable to another file path::
docs/user/advanced.rst-662-
docs/user/advanced.rst-663-    $ export REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE="/usr/local/myproxy_info/cacert.pem"
--
docs/user/advanced.rst-998-   or ``http://localhost@other.com``. It's recommended to terminate full hostnames with a ``/``.
docs/user/advanced.rst-999-
docs/user/advanced.rst-1000-Many of the details of implementing a Transport Adapter are beyond the scope of
docs/user/advanced.rst:1001:this documentation, but take a look at the next example for a simple SSL use-
docs/user/advanced.rst-1002-case. For more than that, you might look at subclassing the
docs/user/advanced.rst-1003-:class:`BaseAdapter <requests.adapters.BaseAdapter>`.
docs/user/advanced.rst-1004-
docs/user/advanced.rst:1005:Example: Specific SSL Version
docs/user/advanced.rst-1006-^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
docs/user/advanced.rst-1007-
docs/user/advanced.rst:1008:The Requests team has made a specific choice to use whatever SSL version is
docs/user/advanced.rst-1009-default in the underlying library (`urllib3`_). Normally this is fine, but from
docs/user/advanced.rst-1010-time to time, you might find yourself needing to connect to a service-endpoint
docs/user/advanced.rst-1011-that uses a version that isn't compatible with the default.
docs/user/advanced.rst-1012-
docs/user/advanced.rst-1013-You can use Transport Adapters for this by taking most of the existing
docs/user/advanced.rst:1014:implementation of HTTPAdapter, and adding a parameter *ssl_version* that gets
docs/user/advanced.rst-1015-passed-through to `urllib3`. We'll make a Transport Adapter that instructs the
docs/user/advanced.rst:1016:library to use SSLv3::
docs/user/advanced.rst-1017-
docs/user/advanced.rst:1018:    import ssl
docs/user/advanced.rst-1019-    from urllib3.poolmanager import PoolManager
docs/user/advanced.rst-1020-
docs/user/advanced.rst-1021-    from requests.adapters import HTTPAdapter
docs/user/advanced.rst-1022-
docs/user/advanced.rst-1023-
docs/user/advanced.rst:1024:    class Ssl3HttpAdapter(HTTPAdapter):
docs/user/advanced.rst:1025:        """"Transport adapter" that allows us to use SSLv3."""
docs/user/advanced.rst-1026-
docs/user/advanced.rst-1027-        def init_poolmanager(self, connections, maxsize, block=False):
docs/user/advanced.rst-1028-            self.poolmanager = PoolManager(
docs/user/advanced.rst-1029-                num_pools=connections, maxsize=maxsize,
docs/user/advanced.rst:1030:                block=block, ssl_version=ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv3)
docs/user/advanced.rst-1031-
docs/user/advanced.rst-1032-Example: Automatic Retries
docs/user/advanced.rst-1033-^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
